ganization.William Viestenz shows how imagining national identity as a sacred absolute within a pluralistic, multicultural state leads to dictatorship, scapegoating, and exceptional violence. Using novels and poetry from the Catalan literary tradition and stalwarts of the Castilian canon, his analysis demonstrates that the sacred is a concept that spills over into key areas of secular political imagination.By the Grace of God offers an original theory of the sacred that challenges our understanding of twentieth-century political thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aReligion and literaturezSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion and politicszSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion in literature. 0aSpanish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311049093008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2019z978311065878140uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266858440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442668584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442668584.jpg  a978-3-11-049093-0  UTP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065878-1  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2019c2014d2019  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL 